@NODE background "The background"
                                Background
                                ----------
Sometimes one have to transfer big files on small media such as floppy
discs. In order to make them fit, the files have to be splitted into
smaller chunks of data. This is exactly what MrSPLIT does.
MrSPLIT is not the only file splitter out there, but it is definitely the
fastest and most efficient of them all.
Most, if not all of the other splitters uses a fixed load buffer. A small
buffer means low speed but requires less memory. A large buffer is faster
(as long as the file is smaller or equal to the buffer size) but requires
much more memory.

MrSPLIT goes a completely different way. The buffersize is determined by an
intelligent(almost) routine that considers filesize and available memory.
This means that MrSPLIT is as fast as the computer allows it to be.

MrSPLIT is also reentrant so you can make it resident with the "resident"
command. This means that you can run many copies of MrSPLIT at the same time
without using more memory than one copy would.
@ENDNODE
@NODE requirements "The requirements"
MrSPLIT should run without any problem on any Amiga in the world with
atleast Kickstart v36+ (that is OS v2.00+) and an MC68000 or MC68020+
But if you would encounter any problems with your system, @{"please let me know." link contact}

MrSPLIT was developed on an old A500 equipped with the following:

                        CPU:       MC68000 7MHZ
                        KICKSTART: v40.70 (OS 3.1)
                        GRAPHICS:  OCS/ECS
                        CHIP:      1.5 MB
                        FAST:      8 MB
                        HARDDRIVE: 126 MB

I know that it's A BIT lowend, but I'm soon going to buy a far better
system. But i will still keep this one though!!!
@ENDNODE
@NODE installation "How to install MrSPLIT"
Installation is very, very easy.

   1. Copy/rename your CPU version to "c:MrSPLIT"
       - Do remember that AmigaOS isn't case sensitive!

   2. Make sure that the "PURE" bit is set. If not, then set it with:
       "protect MrSPLIT P ADD".

   3. That's it! MrSPLIT is now ready to be @{"used" link usage}.

Tip of the day: rename "MrSPLIT" to "split" for easy access !!

Example:

If you have an MC68060 cpu:

"copy MrSPLIT_060 TO c:MrSPLIT" OR "copy MrSPLIT_060 TO c:split"
@ENDNODE
@NODE usage "How to use MrSPLIT"

Template: MrSPLIT @{b}FILE@{ub}/A,@{b}O=OFFSET@{ub}/N/K,@{b}S=SIZE@{ub}/N/K,@{b}BASE@{ub}

@{b}FILE@{ub}         This is the complete path to the big file that you want to split
             into smaller files or to cut out an area from.


@{b}O@{ub} or @{b}OFFSET@{ub}  By default, MrSPLIT works in splitmode, but if you use "OFFSET"
             then MrSPLIT will work in cutmode.

             "OFFSET" describes where in the bigger file that the cutarea
             should start. @{"Examples" link Examp2}


@{b}S@{ub} or @{b}SIZE@{ub}    This is the split or cut size - depending on the workmode.

             In splitmode, the bigger file will be splitted into smaller
             files that will have a filesize of "SIZE".

             In cutmode, a small file with a filesize of "SIZE" will be cut
             out of the bigger file beginning at position "OFFSET".

             By default, "SIZE" equals the filesize of the bigger file.


@{b}BASE@{ub}         This is the basename for the smaller files. This can be either
             a complete path, simply a filename or only a directory. Trailing
             zeroes will be appended to the basename. The number of zeroes
             depends on how many chunks will be created.
             If the basename exceeds 30 chars then the basename will be
             silently truncated to 30 chars. If "BASE" is only a filename or
             if no basename is specified, then the current directory will be
             used for output.

             Note that directories and devices must end with ":" or "/"
             otherwise MrSPLIT treats the name as a file. @{"Examples" link Examp1}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Examp1 "Examples"
Examples:

1.Ram Disk:> MrSPLIT c:copy S=1024
1.Ram Disk:> dir
  Copy0                            Copy1
  Copy2                            Copy3
  Copy4                            Copy5


2.Ram Disk:> MrSPLIT c:copy SIZE=1024 SYS:partfile.
2.Ram Disk:> list sys:
